While with these and such variations thou advancest with insight, in a ship loaded with the treasures of the cell — a great festival full of the marchandisemerchandise of the virtuous — then look with subtlety at the unequal children which are born to thee from apperceptive variations. Thou wilt namely see how every spiritual delight is preceded by the pains of the cross;
how the pleasure of sin, however, is born from bodily comfort; [and thou wilt see] why in the harbour of chastity, spiritual love is caused by spiritual contemplation, which heals the mind. There is nothing secondary without a preceding cause, nor a third virtue without a foregoing one. Thou wilt find growing
in the womb of chastity the wings with which the mind ascends unto divine love, in which one may venture to approach the cloud[l].
